AVIAN INFLUENZA (104): AMERICAS (MEXICO) POULTRY, HPAI H7N3, OIE
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 27 Apr 2022
Source: OIE-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2022 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=52901


High pathogenicity avian influenza viruses (poultry) (Inf. with), Mexico
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Started: 21 Apr 2022
Confirmed: 24 Apr 2022
Reported: 27 Apr 2022
Reason for notification: New strain in a zone or a compartment
Causal agent: Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus [HPAI]
Serotype: H7N3
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: General Cepeda, Coahuila
Started: 21 Apr 2022
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Birds / 74 463 / 74 463 / 543 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Two houses affected in a breeder farm with heavy hens detected after the presence of clinical signs and lesions consistent with the disease were reported.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: Two houses with breeders were identified with highly pathogenic avian influenza H7N3 after clinical suspicion of avian influenza was reported in the State of Coahuila. Emergency and prevention actions were immediately implemented for confirmation with additional tests, and the poultry facility was quarantined in order to contain the outbreak. Sampling is being carried out in commercial and household poultry production units located within a 5-kilometer (3.1 mi) radius of the affected farm to assess the situation. A vaccination campaign was immediately launched for birds in household and commercial farms in neighboring communities. Surveillance has been reinforced at State check and inspection points to prevent movements without official control of live birds and their products and by-products. Poultry farmers have been urged to strengthen biosecurity measures on their farms and to immediately report to official veterinary staff any suspicion of the presence of the disease.

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: Surveillance outside the restricted zone; surveillance within the restricted zone; quarantine
Domestic control measures to be applied: Disinfection; stamping out; slaughter

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Outbreaks / Test / Test date / Result
SENASICA Level 3 Biosecurity Laboratory (national laboratory) / Birds / 1 / Real-time reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) / 22 Apr 2022 / Positive
SENASICA Level 3 Biosecurity Laboratory (national laboratory) / Birds / 1 / Inoculation in chicken embryo / 24 Apr 2022 / Positive


[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Mexico has been affected by highly pathogenic avian influenza, subtype H7N3, since June 2012. The following is a summary of the events occurring in 2020 and 2019:

In April 2020, Mexico reported one outbreak of HPAI H7N3, in the State of Oaxaca. Event information was reported through the OIE 6-monthly report, at https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-smr/view?reportId=149797&period=SEM01&areaId=146&isAquatic=false.

Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Birds / 126 400 / 236 / 0 / 0 / 126 154

From March to October 2019, Mexico reported 33 outbreaks of HPAI H7N3. See the final report on 17 Jan 2020 at https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=14266.

Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Birds / 1 033 917 / 17 682 / 9807 / 558 010 / 312 795

The current outbreak in the municipality of General Cepeda, state of Coahuila, is located about 362 km (225 miles) southwest of the US border at Laredo, Texas. - Mod.CRD

ProMED map:
Mexico: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8702889,14]
